<BYLINE>By LAURA TOLLEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SAN ANTONIO, Texas (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   As world leaders at the seven-nation
economic debated the world's future, their spouses toured this
historic city for a glimpse of Texas' past.
   First Lady Barbara Bush led the summit wives on a 20-minute tour
of Mission San Jose, one of five old Spanish missions still
standing in San Antonio. The fort-like stone mission was built in
1720 by a Franciscan priest for teaching Christianity and European
culture to the Indians.
   Mrs. Bush's guests included France's Danielle Mitterrand,
Canada's Mila Mulroney, Italy's Livia Andreotti and Japan's Sachiyo
Kaifu.
   Britain's Denis Thatcher, the only male summit spouse, skipped
the tour.
   Hannelore Kohl, wife of West German Chancellor Helmut Kohl, and
Marie Delors, wife of European Commission President Jacques Delors,
did not accompany their husbands to Texas.
   After touring the mission, the women went to a private luncheon
at the home Joci and Joe Straus, Jr., longtime friends of the
Bushes, followed by a tour of the Alamo and the renovated Majestic
Theater.
   At one time, San Antonio was a contender as the economic summit
site, but it lost out to Houston, President Bush's adopted hometown.
   The Alamo is the site of the historic 1836 battle between the
Mexican army and men led by Col. William Travis who were fighting
for Texas' independence from Mexico.
   Mexican Gen. Santa Anna's troops greatly outnumbered the Alamo's
defenders, who were besieged for 14 days before the Mexicans
attacked. All 189 of Travis' men were killed.
   The incident gave birth to the battle cry, ``Remember the
Alamo!'' used by other Texans who fought for freedom.
   After visiting San Antonio, the spouses were returning to
Houston, where they planned to tour the Texas Medical Center on
Wednesday, the final day of the summit.
   On Monday, the spouses were guests of Betty and Hugh Liedtkes,
close friends of the Bushes, for a dinner in the upscale Memorial
neighborhood in Houston.
   Liedtke is a wealthy oil man who knew Bush when the president
was in the oil business in Texas before entering politics.
   The menu included quail, gazpacho soup, shrimp creole remoulade,
poached snapper and asparagus. Dessert was called Strawberries
Summit.
   Bush and Liedtke met years ago in West Texas while both were in
the oil business, and they helped form Zapata Petroleum.
Eventually, the company's investors spilt, although Liedtke and
Bush remained friends.
   Liedtke is the former chief of Houston-based Pennzoil Co., the
oil company that won an $10.3 billion judgment in 1985 from Texaco
Inc. over Texaco's takeover of Getty Oil Co. Pennzoil later settled
for $3 billion.
   Liedtke is still chairman of Pennzoil's board.
</TEXT>
