<BYLINE>By LAURA TOLLEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>HOUSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   As the summit leaders focus on global issues,
their spouses have a full schedule of sightseeing and socializing,
starting with a private dinner at friends of President Bush's
Monday night.
   The seven leaders of the industrialized world planned a working
dinner Monday at Bayou Bend, a mansion-turned-museum, while they
spouses were guests of Betty and Hugh Liedtkes.
   The Liedtkes, close friends of both Bush and his wife, Barbara,
invited the spouses to their home for dinner in the upscale
Memorial neighborhood. Liedtke is a wealthy oil man who knew Bush
when the president was in the oil business in Texas before entering
politics.
   On Tuesday, the spouses planned to fly to San Antonio to tour
the Alamo, the Mission San Jose and the renovated Majestic Theatre.
San Antonio also was in the running to host the economic summit,
but the city lost out to Houston, Bush's adopted hometown. .
   The Alamo is the site of the historic 1836 battle between the
Mexican army and a group of men led by Col. William Travis who were
fighting for Texas' independence from Mexico.
   Mexican Gen. Santa Anna's troops greatly outnumbered the Alamo
forces, although historical records do not provide an exact number.
The Mexican soldiers laid siege on the Alamo for 14 days before
attacking.
   All of Travis' men _ 189 _ were killed, and the tragic fight
gave birth to the battle cry, ``Remember the Alamo!'' for other
Texans fighting for freedom.
   After visiting San Antonio, the spouses were to return to
Houston. They also planned to tour the Texas Medical Center on
Wednesday, the final day of the summit.
   Besides Mrs. Bush, the spouses include France's Danielle
Mitterrand, Canada's Mila Mulroney, Italy's Livia Andreotti,
Japan's Sachiyo Kaifu and England's Denis Thatcher, the only male
spouse.
   Hannelore Kohl, wife of West German Chancellor Helmut Kohl, and
Marie Delors, wife of European Commission President Jacques Delors
did not accompany their husbands to Texas.
   The wives of several other local leaders also planned to attend
Monday night's dinner at the Liedtke home. The menu included quail,
gazpacho soup, shrimp creole remoulade, poached snapper and
asparagus. Dessert was called strawberries summit.
   After dinner, the group was to be entertained by a string trio
and a singing duo. The trio's members are all teen-agers.
   Bush and Liedtke met years ago in West Texas while both were in
the oil business, and they helped form Zapata Petroleum.
Eventually, the company's investors spilt, although Liedtke and
Bush remained friends.
   Liedtke is the former chief of Houston-based Pennzoil Co., the
oil company that won an $10.3 billion judgment in 1985 from Texaco
Inc. over Texaco's takeover of Getty Oil Co. Pennzoil later settled
for $3 billion.
   Liedtke is still chairman of Pennzoil's board.
