<BYLINE>By LAURA TOLLEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>HOUSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   First lady Barbara Bush met with young cancer
patients today while the wives of the other summit leaders toured
different parts of the renowned Texas Medical Center.
   The women visited the medical center this morning before their
husbands issued their final communique on the three-day summit at
the George R. Brown Convention Center.
   Mrs. Bush went to the pediatric division of the M.D. Anderson
Cancer Center where she talked with children attending summer
classes at the hospital.
   One of the patients, 15-year-old Denis Lokter, came from the
Soviet Union to get treatment.
   ``We had a wonderful visit from your president,'' Mrs. Bush told
the youth referring Soviet Leader Mikhail Gorbachev's recent trip
to the United States.
   The children gave her a book filled with drawings of dinosaurs
they had made on a computer. They also presented her with a package
of Christmas cards designed by children at the hospital.
   ``I think she was really good,'' said Patrick Chapman, who
turned 7 today.
   ``She called me a nickname _ Fang _ because I don't have a tooth
here,'' he said referring to his missing front tooth.
   Mrs. Bush was joined by France's Danielle Mitterrand, Canada's
Mila Mulroney, Italy's Livia Andreotti, and Japan's Sachiyo Kaifu.
They went to different hospitals at the 600-acre medical center
complex that includes 14 hospitals and two medical schools and four
nursing schools.
   England's Denis Thatcher, the only male spouse, did not visit a
hospital.
   Hannelore Kohl, wife of West German Chancellor Helmut Kohl, and
Marie Delors, wife of European Commission President Jacques Delors
did not accompany their husbands to Texas.
   On Tuesday, Mrs. Bush took the four women to San Antonio to
visit an 18th century mission and the Alamo, while Thatcher visited
his son, Mark, in Dallas.
   ``Nobody can come to Texas without seeing the Alamo,'' Mrs. Bush
told the crowd of several hundred people who braved the heat and
lined up along police barricades to cheer the first ladies.
   ``I wanted to show off a different part of Texas. I wanted them
to see a side of Texas that you might not see any place else, not
only in Texas but in this country,'' she said.
   ``You've really turned out for us and given us a wonderful
day.'' she said.
   At the Alamo, San Antonio Mayor Lila Cockrell gave the women
proclamations saying they were all ``alcaldes,'' or mayors, of the
original San Antonio.
   The Alamo is the site of the historic 1836 battle between the
Mexican army and a group of men led by Col. William Travis who were
fighting for Texas' independence from Mexico.
   Mexican Gen. Santa Anna's troops greatly outnumbered the Alamo
forces, although historical records do not provide an exact number.
The Mexican soldiers laid siege on the Alamo for 14 days before
attacking.
   All 189 of Travis' men were killed, and the tragic fight gave
birth to the battle cry, ``Remember the Alamo!''
   Earlier, the women were greeted by about 900 children at the
Majestic Theater, a palatial theater built in 1929 and restored and
reopened last August.
   The children, from the city's parks and recreation program, were
told about their prestigious visitors only at the last minute. They
cheered and waved miniature Texas flags as the women entered the
ornate theater.
   The spouses also visited the Mission San Jose where they heard
traditional mariachi music.
   The mission, established in 1720 by a Franciscan priest, is one
of five old Spanish missions still standing in San Antonio.
</TEXT>
</DOC>

