<HEAD>Austin Urged to Rename Bowie High</HEAD>
<DATELINE>AUSTIN, Texas (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Hispanic and black leaders are urging
Austin school officials to name a new high school after someone
other than Alamo hero James Bowie, arguing that Bowie was a slave
trader.
   Gary Bledsoe, president of the NAACP's Austin chapter, said
Bowie isn't the kind of person whose name should be on a school.
   ``The plain and simple truth, according to some of the most
noted Texas historians ... is that Jim Bowie smuggled slaves into
North America, sold them at vastly inflated prices, owned then,
sold fictitious land grants for Texas land, fraudulently sold land
owned by his in-laws and committed many other heinous and nefarious
acts,'' Bledsoe said.
   Black and Hispanic leaders have suggested naming the school
after a Hispanic. No Austin high school has a Hispanic namesake.
   The Daughters of the Republic of Texas and 420 other people
recommended that the school be named for Bowie. In a March vote,
the Austin Independent School District Board of Trustees approved
Bowie's name for the school with two board members dissenting. For
the matter to be reheard, a board member who voted in favor of
Bowie's name must move for reconsideration. No such motion was made
at the panel's latest meeting Monday.
   A Kentucky native, Bowie was an adventurer who by age 18 had
earned a reputation for riding alligators and wrestling bears. In
1828, he moved to Texas and settled in San Antonio. After first
sharing command at the Alamo with William B. Travis, Bowie fell ill
and died on March 6, 1836, when Mexican soldiers captured the
mission. A county and a city in Texas are named for him.
   The National Association for the Advancement of Colored People
and others sent a letter complaining of the name choice to the
school board April 11.
</TEXT>
</DOC>

