<HEAD>Group Scraps Plans to Buy `Bowie' Knife</HEAD>
<DATELINE>HOUSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A $3.5 million offer for a knife believed to have
belonged to James Bowie during the battle of the Alamo was
withdrawn because the dagger's owner refused to have it tested for
authenticity.
   Spirit of the Alamo, a non-profit fund-raising group, dropped
the offer, president John Stokes said Saturday.
   Bartley Dean Moore of Riverside, Calif., said family lore has it
that a young Mexican soldier found the knife after the mission fell
in 1836. In 1890, the soldier gave the knife to Moore's grandfather
in Texas to settle a $5 debt, the story goes.
   Museum curators and other experts discounted the claim.
   The fund-raising group, formed last year, had agreed to pay $3.5
million if the knife proved genuine, but wanted tests to determine
its age and metal content.
   All 187 American defenders, including Bowie and Davy Crockett,
were killed in the 13-day siege of the Alamo. Legend credits Bowie
with inventing what is now known as the bowie knife.
</TEXT>
