<HL> So Does This Mean That Texas Remains a Territory of Mexico? </HL>
<AUTHOR> Paul Duke Jr. (WSJ Staff) </AUTHOR>
<SO> </SO>
<TEXT>
   Oil prices slide. 
Real estate goes bust. 
Banks collapse. 
The Dallas Cowboys notch their first losing season in two decades. 

   Texans have seen plenty of woes in recent years. 
Now, to top it all off, even the value of their printed paper is plunging. 
And not just any paper, but Texas's proudest heritage, including certain copies of its own 1836 Declaration of Independence from Mexico, which sold for up to $30,000. 

   A number of them have turned out to be phonies. 
Someone -- no one knows who -- has been "diddling around with the stuff of Texas history," says an angry Don Carleton, director of the Barker Texas History Center at the University of Texas. 

   And they've been doing so for the past 15 years, according to Austin-based publisher and rare-book dealer W. Thomas Taylor, who alerted Texas booksellers to the problem earlier this month. 
Mr. Taylor himself unwittingly sold several of the phony documents. 

   The duped also include such patriotic Texas bigwigs as Gov. William Clements, as well as numerous libraries and universities, including the Barker Center. 
It owns a fake copy of a particularly sacred Texas text, Col. William Barrett Travis's "Victory or Death" letter, penned just as the Mexican forces closed in on the Alamo. 

   All of the forgeries purport to be general-distribution circulars printed in the 1830s and '40s, during the Republic of Texas era. 
But the typefaces used, says Mr. Taylor, weren't invented until decades later. 
Aside from that big gaffe, the fastidious forgers dotted some i's that went undotted in the originals. 
Mr. Taylor figures a total of about 100 false documents are in circulation, and embarassed booksellers around the state are apologetically returning their customers' money. 

   But not all Texas tycoons were taken in. 
A while back, H. Ross Perot was offered a Travis circular. 
Experts at Yale University, which has a verified Travis letter, were skeptical, and Mr. Perot passed. 

   Still, that hasn't stopped others from offering him a supposed original U.S. Declaration of Independence and the sword General Cornwallis surrendered to George Washington. 
Says Mr. Perot: "There are days when I think people must believe I'm the biggest patsy around." 

</TEXT>
</DOC>

