<HL> Utility Holds Talks On Buying System In San Antonio </HL>
<AUTHOR> Dianna Solis (WSJ Staff) </AUTHOR>
<SO> </SO>
<CO> CSR HOU </CO>
<IN> UTI TNM NUK </IN>
<TEXT>
   Central &amp; South West Corp., a utility holding company, said it has held "exploratory talks" with the city of San Antonio, Texas, regarding purchasing the municipal electric system. 

   "Our discussion was only preliminary and philosophical and no negotiation regarding price or terms occurred" with San Antonio, the nation's 10th-largest city, said Merle Borchelt, chairman and chief executive officer of the Dallas-based holding company. 

   Central &amp; South West, which serves 1.5 million customers in four states, has indicated repeatedly that it is interested in acquiring a fifth utility. 
Its dominant unit, Central Power &amp; Light Co., owns a 25.2% stake in the $5.3 billion South Texas nuclear project. 
City Public Service of San Antonio owns a 28% stake in the same nuclear plant. 

   If a merger were to take place, the combined stake of 53.2% would give the Central &amp; South West unit the majority interest in the nuclear project and make the parent company the largest electricity provider in Texas. 

   The city of Austin holds a 16% stake in the South Texas Project, 90 miles south of Houston. 
Houston Lighting &amp; Power Co., a utility unit of Houston Industries Inc., is the managing partner with a 30.8% stake in the two-unit nuclear project. 
The three other partners have been in yet unresolved litigation with Houston Lighting &amp; Power for several years over cost overruns and alleged mismanagement of the project. 

   In 1987, Central &amp; South West had net income of $372 million, or $3.92 a share, on revenue of $2.4 billion. 
Mr. Borchelt said the possible purchase of City Public Service of San Antonio would require extensive negotiations and approvals by regulatory agencies. 
San Antonio Mayor Henry Cisneros met with Mr. Borchelt this week regarding the possible purchase, a Central &amp; South West spokesman said. 

   Mr. Cisneros couldn't be reached for comment on the terse announcement made late last night by the Dallas company. 
A City Public Service spokeswoman shed no light on the talks. 

   San Antonio, a city of about one million people, is best known for its military past and present. 
Its economy remains fueled by both facts. 
Helping to fill city coffers are its military complexes and tourism, much of the latter centered on the Alamo mission, where the U.S. was defeated by Mexico when Texas was still part of that nation. 
The city, 150 miles north of the Mexican border, also has a fledgling biotechnology industry. 

   City Public Service serves about 500,000 customers in Bexar County, where San Antonio is, and seven adjoining counties. 
Bexar, the nation's 10th fastest-growing county, has considerable electric needs. 
The city's peak demand this summer was 2,663 megawatts while it currently has an electrical capacity of 3,200,000 kilowatts. 

</TEXT>
