<HEAD>Tower Acknowledges Infidelity But Vows to Keep Fighting for Defense
Post</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: INSERT 6th graf with ex-wife charges bgng ``Tower's second...;
SUB grafs 11-12 pvs to add Alamao details bgng ``Asked whether...</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LAWRENCE L. KNUTSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   John Tower made an extraordinary public
confession of marital infidelity today but vowed to keep fighting to
win confirmation as defense secretary by invoking the words of the
commander at the Alamo: ``I shall never surrender or retreat.''
   In an appearance at the National Press Club, Tower also said he
regards his weekend oath to quit drinking if he wins confirmation as
``sacred...and I can assure you I will abide by it.''
   Tower fielded questions about his confirmation ordeal as Vice
President Dan Quayle conceded the Bush admininistration is currently
short of the votes needed to ratify the appointment, and as Senate
Majority Leader George Mitchell announced his opposition.
   At the White House, spokesman Marlin Fitzwater said President
Bush was continuing to lobby senators personally in search of
additional votes.
   Asked whether he had ever broken his wedding vows, Tower, twice
divorced and now single, said, ``As a matter of fact, I have broken
wedding vows. I think I am probably not alone in that connection.''
   Tower's second wife, Lilla, alleged ``marital misconduct'' in
court filings in the couple's divorce case.
   Tower's appearance marked the latest turn in the struggle by the
Bush administration _ as well as the former Texas senator _ to
salvage the nomination against solid Democratic opposition in the
Senate.
   Tower has been struggling against concerns about his drinking
habits, allegations of womanizing and questions over possible
conflicts of interest stemming from his employment as a defense
industry consultant.
   In his remarks, Tower also turned aside a question of whether his
appointment was a political payoff for having headed a commission
that gave Bush a clean bill of health in the Iran-Contra scandal of
the Reagan administration. He said congressional investigators also
found nothing to implicate Bush, and said, ``I wonder what kind of
payoff they're going to get.''
   Tower showed flashes of humor and grit by turn at the press club
rostrum.
   Asked how he felt about his predicament, he said ``a little bit
like the fellow who was immersed in tar and feathers and was being
ridden out of town on a rail. He said, really gentlemen if it were
not for the honor I'd rather hitchhike.''
   Asked whether he would ask that his name be withdrawn from
nomination, he replied by quoting from the last letter written by
Lt. Col. William Barrett Travis, whom he identified as the leader of
the Texans who fought and died at the Alamo: ``I shall never
surrender or retreat.''
   Tower paused briefly and said, ``I am a little sorry I brought up
the Alamo analogy. It just occurred to me what happened at the Alamo
just 10 days after Travis wrote that letter.'' Texas defenders were
wiped out by Mexican Gen. Santa Anna's forces.
   Asked what had angered him most about his confirmation fight, he
said there were no clearly defined standards against which he was
being judged. He noted that several senators have said that the
secretary of defense, as the commander of U.S. military forces
behind only the president, must adhere to a higher standard. ``I
accept that...but my question is how much,'' he said.
   He then asked whether it is ``acceptable for members late in the
evening who had a few drinks in hideaways...to come onto the floor
late in the evening and vote on vital issues of nuclear
deterrence,'' or to accept speaking fees, campaign contributions and
paid vacations ``from special interests who have a vested interest
in the legislative process.''
   There was no letup in the political storm surrounding the
nomination, as Fitzwater charged Democrats with turning the
appointment into a partisan struggle.
   The spokesman claimed some senators are ``starting to have second
thoughts about the words they used'' to describe Tower.
   Quayle claimed progress for the administration lobbying campaign,
as well.
   ``We don't have 50 votes yet. But we're moving in that direction,
and I'll be the 51st,'' he said, referring to his ability to cast a
tie-breaking vote in the Senate, where the Democrats hold a 55-45
advantage.
   Key Republicans said they would meet later in the day to decide
whether to seek a delay in the beginning of the debate on the
nomination, which has drawn widespread opposition from Democrats.
   Tower has been battling questions about his drinking habits,
allegations of womanizing and concerns about his acceptance of
thousands of dollars in defense consultants' fees, and Mitchell
addressed those issues in his speech ion the Senate.
   The Maine Democrat said he was troubled by Tower's work as a
defense consultant. ``He received payment while it was widely
assumed that he might be a nominee for defense secretary if
President Bush were elected,'' the Democratic leader said.
   Turning to the controversy over Tower's personal conduct,
Mitchell said ``it is not moral perfection or the qualifications of
senators that are at issue here.''
   ``Public officials have a right to a private life,'' he said.
``They do not have a right to engage publicly in behavior which
could interfere with the discharge of their public duties.''
   ``A single lapse in judgment _ or perhaps even a few _ should not
disqualify an individual from public service,'' Mitchell continued.
   ``But when the lapses in judgment form a pattern of many
incidents spanning many years, and when there is insufficient
evidence to demonstrate that the pattern has been broken, then there
are reasonable grounds to question whether the individual possesses
the qualities necessary for the uniquely demanding job of the
secretary of defense.''
   Mitchell's position was widely anticipated, particularly since
all Democrats who have expressed an opinion on the nomination have
opposed it, and almost all Republicans have endorsed it.
   But at the same time, the Democratic leader said he hoped the
Tower struggle would not have ``an adverse impact on relations''
between the Democratic majority in the Senate and the administration.
   ``I do not believe any senator's decision should be based upon
partisan considerations,'' he said. ``This is a personal decision
for each senator to make...''
   Quayle made his comments during a photo session with Guatemalan
President Vinicio Cerezo.
   Asked if Tower's nomination could still be salvaged, he said, ``I
think so. I hope so.''
   He said he was not worried about Pentagon operations, saying,
``The Pentagon is ongoing right now'' under acting Secretary William
H. Taft IV.
   ``There will not be any interruption until we get a new secretary
of defense,'' Quayle said.
   The White House vowed to fight on in Tower's behalf, and
Fitzwater said Bush would be meeting with ``one or two senators'' on
the question today.
   ``We're still hopeful. We're still going to keep working it ...
We'll just keep up the good fight and see how it goes,'' Fitzwater
said.
   The debate over Tower has become increasingly partisan in recent
days. Senate Republican Leader Bob Dole, after a meeting with Bush
at the White House on Tuesday night, said the opposition ``is an
affront to the president of the United States who was elected last
November to make these nominations.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>

