<HEAD>Pell `Out Of It,' Says Schneider</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CRANSTON, R.I. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   U.S. Rep. Claudine Schneider says voters
regard 71-year-old Sen. Claiborne Pell as being ``out of it.''
   Pell's campaign manager said Miss Schneider was becoming
``desperate'' in her campaign against the senator, who is ahead in
the polls.
   ``She sees him daily,'' said Mary Beth Cahill. ``She knows
that's not true.''
   Before a news conference, Miss Schneider, a 43-year-old
Republican, said:
   ``People say to me they saw Claiborne out campaigning and they
say, `I didn't realize ... he was so out of it.'''
   Democrat Pell declined comment on the matter.
</TEXT>
<BYLINE>---</BYLINE>
<HEAD>Lola Perpich Pounding Air Waves as Governor Pounds Grunseth's
Personal Life</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ST. PAUL, Minn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Lola Perpich has taken an unusually high
profile in her husband's Democratic gubernatorial re-election
campaign, appearing in 30-second ads saying everything is rosy
under the Perpich administration.
   The current ad shows a vase of white roses, with hands from an
unseen person inserting a rose into the vase as a narrator tickets
off awards and distinctions to Minnesota.
   The ad closes with a shot of Lola Perpich suggesting that
Minnesota's high quality of life and well-managed government has
come about because ``Rudy makes government work for you.'' There's
a small picture of the governor in the corner.
   The ``Roses'' ads are part of a double-barrelled attack against
Perpich's opponent, Jon Grunseth. While Lola appears on television,
the governor has been dwelling on the details of Grunseth's
divorce.
</TEXT>
<BYLINE>---</BYLINE>
<HEAD>In Texas Politics, The One With The `Famous' Name Has An Edge</HEAD>
<DATELINE>AUSTIN, Texas (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   In previous races for the Texas Railroad
Commission, John Sharp has beaten opponents Sam Ervin and Jack
Daniel.
   Now in his bid for state comptroller, Democrat Sharp is being
challenged by Republican Warren G. Harding Jr. That was the name of
a former Texas treasurer as well as the late president.
   Sharp says he is worried about his latest campaign against yet
another election-year rival with a celebrated name.
   ``Whenever a famous name is taken for granted, they win,'' Sharp
told a news conference.
   The Ervin in Sharp's race was not the famous Watergate senator
and Daniel had no connection to the Tennessee whiskey.
   Among the other names on the ballot in Texas this year.
   Gene Kelly is trying to win a seat on the Texas Supreme Court.
Sam Houston Clinton is seeking re-election to the Texas Court of
Criminal Appeals.
   Voters in San Antonio could elect Bart Simpson - a young
businessman and not the sharp-tongued cartoon character - to the
Texas Legislature.
   Two write-in candidates for governor hope to take advantage of
their names. James ``Jim'' Wright is not the former U.S. House
speaker. Writer Lloyd ``Alamo'' Scott hopes voters will Remember
the Alamo when they cast their ballots.
</TEXT>
<BYLINE>---</BYLINE>
<HEAD>Poll Shows Kopetski Has Lead</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PORTLAND, Ore. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Democratic challenger Mike Kopetski has
edged past U.S. Rep. Denny Smith in a hotly contested congressional
race, according to a poll conducted for a Portland television
station.
   The survey, conducted for KPTV, showed Kopetski favored by 49
percent, compared with 41 percent for Smith. Te percent were
undecided. Of those who considered themselves most likely to vote,
Kopetski was favored by 51 percent and Smith by 41 percent.
   The poll, by Bardsley &amp; Neidhart Inc., has a margin of error of
plus or minus 4.9 percent.
   The random telephone survey questioned 404 registered voters
between Oct. 2 and 7.
</TEXT>
</DOC>

