<HEAD>TRAVEL: Texas Sea World</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto NY707</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVID SEDENO</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SAN ANTONIO, Texas (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Shamu, Namu and Kandu are readying a
killer of a sea show that organizers hope will fishtail with the
Alamo and the city's River Walk.
   While the killer whales swim around in a 7 million gallon tank,
gardeners are putting the final landscaping touches on Sea World of
Texas, a $140 million, 250-acre facility billed as the nation's
largest marine theme park.
   The park's ``Big Splash'' opening is set for May 28, but
workers, animals and trainers are already performing in rehearsals
for visitors.
   Sea World, 13 miles northwest of downtown San Antonio, will be
open year-round. It is expected to employ 2,000 people during its
peak summer season, generate a $25 million annual payroll and
attract 3 million visitors bearing another $300 million yearly for
the park's and South Texas' economies.
   City and tourist industry officials have looked at Sea World as
a magnet for tourists to help the state diversify from its
dependency on petroleum, but Sea World chairman George Becker warns
against expecting too much too soon.
   ``I've cautioned a few people that we'll do the very best that
we can, but not to rest on their laurels and expect us to be the
end-all and the answer to all of their business problems,'' he said.
   Visitors can expect to see the park's star, Shamu, a two-ton
killer whale that was among the fish and animals brought in from
three other Sea World parks around the country.
   Shamu will perform in a 4,500-seat stadium. At other, smaller
stadiums, dolphins, seals, sea lions, walruses and other animals
will show their stuff, too.
   Skiers will perform acrobatics in a 12-acre lake, and visitors
can walk across the United States via a one-acre ``map'' of the
country.
   There are restaurants, lounges, a disco for teen-agers and a
playground for children. There also is Cypress Gardens West, a
botanical center where a variety of flowers will bloom year-round.
   San Antonio tourism already generates more than $1 billion
annually, with lures like the Alamo and the River Walk.
   Texas is home to Six Flags of Texas in Arlington and to
AstroWorld in Houston, both of which attract about 1.7 million
visitors a year each.
   Tourist industry officials believe Sea World will help, not
hurt, those amusement parks.
   ``It's actually going to help them because it completes the
triangle of from San Antonio, Houston and the Dallas-Fort Worth
area,'' said Larry Todd, director of the Texas Tourist Agency.
   He said Sea World is following the lead of other tourist
attractions by promoting Texas first and its location second.
   ``I don't think tourism is a panacea, but it's all fresh, new
money and it's an immediate boost to the economy and it's rapidly
becoming one of our top industries,'' Todd said.
   ``We Texans had better face the fact that tourism is an industry
whose time has come. We have sat back and been dependent on oil and
agriculture and haven't needed tourism, and now all of a sudden we
need it and we need to market Texas intelligently,'' he said.
   (Sea World's one-day admission is $18.95 for adults and $15.95
for senior citizens (55 and older) and children 3-11. A 12-month
pass is $49 for adults and $39 for children. Founders Club pass,
available until May 28, is $125 and offers special discounts and is
good for admission through Dec. 31, 1991. Sea World sales office
number is 512-523-3400.)
</TEXT>
