<HEAD>Soviet Officer Visiting Oklahoma After Seeing Demonstrators In
Texas</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Fixes dateline; INSERTS 1 graf after 3rd graf pvs, `This
is...', to add quote from Akhromeyev, picking up 4th graf pvs,
`Saturday morning...'.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By DOUG FERGUSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>OKLAHOMA CITY (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Soviet Union's top-ranking military
officer saw traditional Indian dancing and an old-fashioned cowboy
shoot-'em-up Saturday on a whirlwind visit to Oklahoma after
protesters in Texas told his delegation to ``Go home, murderers.''
   Soviet Marshal Sergei F. Akhromeyev and his group also got to
see cattle roping, trick roping and square dancing as the state
provided the visitors with a taste of Western heritage.
   This is the first visit of the ranking Soviet military leader to
the United States. The weeklong tour of several cities is designed
to give the Soviet officers the chance to see typical American life
in addition to the military aspects.
   ``The times really have been changing for the better, and are
changing for the better, because of the politically courageous
decisions by our two political leaders,'' Ahkromeyev said shortly
before the evening ended. ``We need to carry out and maintain a
stable and friendly relationship.''
   Saturday morning, when the Soviet delegation was at the Alamo in
San Antonio, two demonstrators told Akhromeyev that he did not
belong at Texas' most famous shrine. But Akhromeyev's visit there
was more peaceful than the greeting he received upon his arrival in
San Antonio on Friday night.
   About 50 demonstrators chanted ``Go home, murderers!'' when
Akhromeyev and several other Soviet officers showed up at the
Institute of Texan Cultures.
   ``I feel it's really a crime to invite these killers here when
they are committing genocide in Afghanistan and terrorism around
the world,'' said Sayed Nasir, a mechanical engineer from
Afghanistan.
   Oklahoma Gov. Henry Bellmon was host for Saturday evening's
entertainment. During the festivities, Akhromeyev was presented
with an Indian headdress, and he and several other Soviet officials
were invited to try their hand at branding some cattle. None took
up the offer.
   Ten-year-old Charlie Ward was one of a group of youngsters who
took part in a trick roping demonstration for the entourage. ``It
made me feel good,'' he said afterward. ``It's the kind of
friendship between the Soviets and Americans, getting to know
them.''
   Earlier in the day, Akhromeyev and U.S. Adm. William Crowe,
chairman of the Joint Chiefs of Staff, toured the University of
Oklahoma campus. Crowe is a native of Oklahoma.
   ``I think it's a positive thing that these two guys can
communicate on all levels,'' said an onlooker, Neil Kingsley.
``They seem to understand each other.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>

