<HEAD>Alleged Drug Kingpin, Two Others Escape from Private Texas Prison</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: SUBS 6th graf, `Jonas identified...', with 3 grafs to add
details of `Jet Set' allegations, picking up 7th graf pvs, `Compton
and...'. SUBS from 15th graf, `Wackenhut officials...', to end to
CORRECT that gun believed to be .25-caliber sted 25mm; delete
redundant reference to Coral Gables, add detail on prison
population.</NOTE>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto Upcoming</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SAN ANTONIO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An alleged drug kingpin and two other inmates
escaped from a privately run prison across from the police station
after one of them pulled a gun on a guard, authorities said.
   Five federal agencies plus Mexican, Texas and local officials
were searching today for the men who escaped Sunday evening. They
include Mario Alberto Salinas Trevino, who federal authorities
allege masterminded one of the largest drug-smuggling and
money-laundering rings between Texas and Mexico.
   Police said the three men may be heading to Mexico and are
considered armed and dangerous. At its closest point, the border is
about 100 miles away.
   Salinas, 37, was among 25 people arrested in March 1989 in a
drug operation dubbed ``Operation Jet Set.''
   U.S. Marshal Bill Jonas said $10 million was seized from Salinas
then, and he's suspected of having up to $10 million in drug money
stashed in a hideaway either in Texas or Mexico.
   Prosecutors charge that between 1983 and 1989, a drug ring
Salinas helped run was responsible for transporting more than
46,000 pounds of marijuana and 1,900 pounds of cocaine. The ring
allegedly distributed the drugs throughout Texas, Pennsylvania,
California, Illinois, Florida and Massachusetts.
   The ring also is accused of laundering of more than $7.6
million, using financial institutions in San Antonio and Roma,
Texas and San Ysidro, Calif., to launder narcotics profits.
   Jonas identified the other inmates as Charlie Edward Compton,
58, and Juan Chapa Garza, 44. Compton was awaiting trial on federal
charges of possession of cocaine with intent to distribute. Chapa
was charged with possession of marijuana with intent to distribute.
The charges were not related to the ``Jet Set'' probe.
   Compton and Salinas are U.S. citizens, Jonas said. He wasn't
sure about Chapa's nationality.
   The three were cellmates at the Central Texas Parole Violators
Facility, a minimum- to medium-security prison in the old Bexar
County jail operated by Wackenhut Corp. of Coral Gables, Fla.
   Compton summoned a guard, claiming he was ill, and pulled a
handgun on him shortly before 9 p.m., Jonas said.
   The three then locked up two guards in the closet and
overpowered another guard on the ground floor before seizing the
security control panels and opening a door, Jonas said. They fled
on foot.
   According to police reports, San Antonio police weren't notified
of the jailbreak until nearly an hour after the three men had
escaped.
   But Wackenhut spokesman Pat Cannan said police were notified 15
to 20 minutes after the jail break by the guard on the ground
floor, who was tied up outside.
   ``It took him about 15 to 20 minutes to get unloose and he ran
straight across the street to the police department,'' Cannan said.
``That was the proper thing to do.''
   Jonas said he had no indication that Wackenhut had delayed the
reporting unneccessarily.
   Wackenhut officials speculate the pistol was smuggled into the
prison during Easter Day visiting hours, Cannan said. He spoke in a
telephone interview from Coral Gables. Jonas said the gun was
believed to be a .25-caliber.
   ``We suspect it was brought in by a visitor,'' he said. Cannan
said the prison screens visitors, but he declined to give details.
   The inmates were being held in the private facility for the U.S.
Marshal's Service, Cannan said. The 620-capacity prison was housing
583 people Sunday, about 100 of them Marshal's Service prisoners,
Cannan said. The prison has 125 guards, 20 to 25 per shift, he said.
   The Marshal's Service has summoned assistance from the U.S. Drug
Enforcement Adminstration, FBI, Customs Service, Immigration and
Naturalization Service and Mexican customs, Jonas said. State and
local officials also were involved in the search.
</TEXT>
